         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Decr. 24/62 ¶ Dear Dr Mueller ¶  ¶ I write a few lines to thank you again for the 2d &amp; 3d of exchanges, first duly received &amp; acknowledged some weeks ago. ¶  Pamplin has also written in your name that...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">62.12.24</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M4, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Decr. 24/62</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Dear Dr Mueller</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I write a few lines to thank you again for the 2d &amp; 3d of exchanges, first duly received &amp; acknowledged some weeks ago.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The boxes of Herbarium specimens sent to Kew for Bentham’s use while writing <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Flora Australiensis</seg>. See J Hooker to M, 11 April 1862.</p>
               </note> Pamplin has also written in your name that the binding bill should be transferred to your acct. if your <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Establishment</hi>
               </seg> pays. I can have no objection to this as it was a private affair between you &amp; Henslows family so far as I was concerned, I was most anxious that you should not think the lot a <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">shabby one</hi>
               </seg>!<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M was purchasing some items from the library of J. S. Henslow, and Hooker arranged with M’s agent, Pamplin, for a run of journals to be bound; see J. Hooker to M, 11 April 1862.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am now doing <name key="Combretaceae">Combretaceae</name>, having just begun, &amp; find little novelty except your fine thing which I have not looked at yet but which I cannot doubt is a noble &amp; excellent good genus, I am glad you have described it — the Fragmentum with it has not come to hand yet.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Macropteranthes leichhardtii</seg> (B62.09.01, p. 91), see M to G. Bentham, 24 September 1862. Hooker was the author of the <name key="Combretaceae">Combretaceae</name> in Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83), vol 1, pt. 2, pp. 684-90.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am sending you some good odds &amp; ends of duplicate plants through Pamplin which will I hope prove useful to you. Bentham will arrange about copies of Gen. Plant.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83).</p>
               </note> I have made a frightful blunder in <name key="Zieria">Zieria</name> where I say "Australiae tropicae &amp; subtropicae orient. incolae"<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862–83), vol 1, pt. 1, p. 291.</p>
               </note>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>— for <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">tropicae</hi>
               </seg> read <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">temperatae</hi>
               </seg> of course. Bentham is working desperately hard on the Flora.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>My Father is remarkably well, as busy as ever with his Ferns, I with <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Welwitschia">Welwitschia</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                     <p rend="Footnote"
                        style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See J. Hooker to M, 20 September 1862.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg> &amp; "Genera Plantarum" — he is counting on the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">unrivalled</hi>
               </seg> wood of Victoria from the Exhibition.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>That is, to receive for Kew the woods described in the catalogue of the International Exhibition, London 1862 (1862), p. 144, item 226; W. Hooker was a member of the jury for the relevant section. The jury’s comments of which on some of the specimens of timber in the 'magnificent collection' were published in International Exhibition, London 1862 (1863), Class 4, Section C, p. 36. See M to W. Hooker, 20 December 1862.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Ever dear Mueller most ty yrs</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Jos D Hooker</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Col. Munro, writes me word that the exquisite grass you wrote about &amp; enclosed<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See J. Hooker to M, 20 September 1862.</p>
               </note> (like a <name key="Lappago">Lappago</name>) is a totally new form of <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Panicum</hi>
               </seg> for which he proposes the mss name <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">pachy[g]luma</hi>
               </seg> but he does this in ignorance that you will probably publish it (he will not so there is no fear of your clashing.) I am writing to him &amp; will tell him you will publish it under what name you think proper in the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Fragmenta</hi>
               </seg> probably.<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M published the grass as <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Panicum munroi</seg> (B66.12.04, p. 204).</p>
               </note> - I have not hunted for it through the Herb. but could not find it in <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Panicum</hi>
               </seg> or <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Paspalum">Paspalum</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
